text: Beyond her terrifying experience, Recy Taylor is a representation of the many communities this Administration has chosen to leave behind. I am proud of my colleagues in @OfficialCBC, @HouseDemocrats, and @HouseDemWomen that will be wearing red pins in memoriam of Recy at #SOTU.

Recy Taylor represents the voice of many marginalized women who have spoken up, spoken out and have long been ignored. The transformative movement that’s happening in this country must include amplifying the voices of victims that we, in some cases, chose not to hear.

I am excited to announce that I have the honor of bringing Rose Gunter, niece of Recy Taylor, as my guest to #SOTU. Her aunt's legacy lives on through the many women and allies who are advancing the transformative #MeToo and #TimesUp movements in this country.

text: On Maternal Health Awareness day and every day we must support increasing access to adequate and essential healthcare that mothers and children deserve. Allowing new mothers to gain healthcare is the first step and I will continue to fight for this necessary legislation.

That’s why I introduced the Healthy MOM Act - designates pregnancy as a Qualifying Life Event, creating a special enrollment period so that pregnant women can get the care they need to have healthy pregnancies and healthy infants.
Health insurance coverage during pregnancy can lead to healthier pregnancies and better birth outcomes but could also generate health care cost saving.

Did you know that if an uninsured woman discovers she is pregnant outside the open enrollment period, she will likely be unable to obtain affordable coverage with appropriate benefits for most or all of her pregnancy?

It is a tragedy that so many preventable deaths still occur, especially given that many life-saving maternal and child health solutions are well-known and cost-effective. Yet these simple solutions remain elusive for far too many women and children.

It's Maternal Health Awareness Day in New Jersey and I'm so proud to see so many people devoted to raising awareness and redoubling our efforts to meet the urgent need for better maternal health care around the world. https://t.co/gNO3ozicVa

And only one involved impersonation fraud, which is what photo ID laws protect against. (3/3) #votingrights
In that time frame, hundreds of millions of votes were cast yet only 38 cases were brought to trial (2/3)
Between 2002 and 2005, the @TheJusticeDept made prosecuting voter fraud a top priority. (1/3)
The #VotingRightsAct, which had previously curtailed dangerous voting restrictions was gutted in 2013 by the Supreme Court. #VRA
#VoterID laws disproportionately impact communities of color, women, seniors, students, and low income individuals. #votingrights
Since 2010, 22 states have passed laws that make it more difficult for Americans to vote. #votingrights
.@HouseGOP, despite so many opportunities to move forward we’re rolling backward.  #votingrights
We seem to have traveled back to a dark place in our nation’s history when it was both legal and common to limit access to polling places.
Let's talk about how we can use digital advancements to expand access instead of trying to manufacture excuses to limit access. (2/2)
Let's talk about technology. I acknowledge that there are very real challenges we face in bringing technology to the ballot box. (1/2)
Congress should get involved in offering individuals like these one of the most fundamental rights that we have as Americans. But we’re not.
Unfortunately we ban millions of these Americans from the ballot box, despite their rehabilitation. (3/3) #VotingRights
They’ve put in the effort to change, and have come back to society as taxpaying, law abiding citizens. (2/3)
We have Americans that have made mistakes in their pasts but have completed their sentences for non-violent convictions (1/3)
Same day registration offered in one state but not the next. (2/2) #votingrights
States have different voting systems: early voting is allowed in some places but not others (1/2)
.@HouseGOP, there’s quite a bit to fix when it comes to #votingrights, yet Congress isn’t willing to do anything about it.
Instead of embracing every opportunity to improve and facilitate one of the cornerstones of our democracy, we’re allowing it to crumble.
